    {
      "source": "evaluator",
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my data science midterm and im a bit stuck on regularization. can u explain the main difference between L1 and L2 regularization specifically in terms of what they do to the model coefficients?"
    },
    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure thing! L1 and L2 regularization are both techniques to prevent overfitting by adding a penalty term to the loss function, but they do it in different ways. L1 regularization, also known as Lasso, adds a penalty equal to the absolute value of the magnitude of the coefficients. This can lead to some coefficients being exactly zero, effectively performing feature selection. On the other hand, L2 regularization, also known as Ridge, adds a penalty equal to the square of the magnitude of the coefficients, which tends to shrink the coefficients but not necessarily to zero. This can help in distributing the error among all the features, rather than focusing on just a few. In other words, L1 can be thought of as a way to make your model more sparse, while L2 is more about making it more robust by distributing the error.",
